<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,500,2037]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Color and pilosity. Body covered by short, brown pubescence and semi-recumbent golden setae. Head dorsally and ventrally dark brown. Eyes red. Antennae and legs shining yellow, except tibiae and tarsi brown. Rostrum shining brown except for segment IV dark black; genital segments shining brown. Pronotum with anterior transverse yellow band. Venter of abdomen dark grey; abdominal sternite VII centrally with black pubescence.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,500,2037]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,374,788,813]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Apterous male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[390,486,788,813]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 1–4. 1" captionStart-1="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId-0="2.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionStartId-1="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox-0="[222,1352,231,1869]" captionTargetBox-1="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId-0="figure-74@2.[213,1373,190,1894]" captionTargetId-1="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId-0="2" captionTargetPageId-1="3" captionText-0="FIGURES 1–4. 1. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, dorsal habitus without appendages. Scale 0.10 mm. 2. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, antenna, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 3. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.10 mm. 4. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, paramere, lateral view. Scale 0.025 mm." captionText-1="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271484" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5271484/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 1–7</figureCitation>
) BL: 1.86; HL: 0.34; HW: 0.56; ANT I–IV: 0.24, 0.22, 0.28, 0.30; INT: 0.32; EYE: 0.12; 
<collectionCode box="[216,253,824,847]" country="Czech Republic" name="Západoceské muzeum v Plzni" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" type="Museum">PL</collectionCode>
: 0.32; 
<collectionCode box="[332,377,824,847]" country="Thailand" name="Paleontological Collections" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">PW</collectionCode>
: 0.78; FORELEG: FEM: 0.52, TIB: 0.44, TAR I: 0.04, TAR II: 0.14; MIDLEG: FEM: 0.62, TIB: 0.60, TAR I: 0.10, TAR II: 0.22; HINDLEG: FEM: 0.64, TIB: 0.72, TAR I: 0.06, TAR II: 0.18.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,500,2037]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">
Head with midline shining black (
<figureCitation box="[584,650,895,920]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4. 1" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,231,1869]" captionTargetId="figure-74@2.[213,1373,190,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, dorsal habitus without appendages. Scale 0.10 mm. 2. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, antenna, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 3. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.10 mm. 4. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, paramere, lateral view. Scale 0.025 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271484" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271484/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Antennae reaching well beyond pronotum. Antennomere I thickest, curved outward, II widening to apex, 
<collectionCode box="[578,606,932,955]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">III</collectionCode>
cylindrical, IV fusiform (
<figureCitation box="[899,969,932,957]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4. 1" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,231,1869]" captionTargetId="figure-74@2.[213,1373,190,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, dorsal habitus without appendages. Scale 0.10 mm. 2. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, antenna, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 3. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.10 mm. 4. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, paramere, lateral view. Scale 0.025 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271484" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271484/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Rostrum extending slightly past middle of mesosternum. Pronotum covering mesonotum and metanotum; with scattered subcircular punctuations, lacking a median carina (
<figureCitation box="[369,442,1004,1029]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4. 1" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,231,1869]" captionTargetId="figure-74@2.[213,1373,190,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, dorsal habitus without appendages. Scale 0.10 mm. 2. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, antenna, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 3. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.10 mm. 4. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, paramere, lateral view. Scale 0.025 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271484" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271484/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Abdominal connexiva slightly elevated, with posterolateral angles rounded; last abdominal tergite trapezoidal, with posterior margin slightly rounded. Genital segment I rounded (
<figureCitation box="[1345,1418,1039,1064]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4. 1" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,231,1869]" captionTargetId="figure-74@2.[213,1373,190,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, dorsal habitus without appendages. Scale 0.10 mm. 2. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, antenna, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 3. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.10 mm. 4. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, paramere, lateral view. Scale 0.025 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271484" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271484/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Abdominal sternite VII with a broad medial depression (
<figureCitation box="[789,858,1076,1101]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4. 1" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,231,1869]" captionTargetId="figure-74@2.[213,1373,190,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, dorsal habitus without appendages. Scale 0.10 mm. 2. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, antenna, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 3. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.10 mm. 4. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, paramere, lateral view. Scale 0.025 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271484" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271484/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Venter of genital segment I with posterior margin rounded (
<figureCitation box="[258,326,1111,1136]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4. 1" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,231,1869]" captionTargetId="figure-74@2.[213,1373,190,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, dorsal habitus without appendages. Scale 0.10 mm. 2. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, antenna, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 3. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.10 mm. 4. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, paramere, lateral view. Scale 0.025 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271484" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271484/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Genital segment II hidden. Parameres elongate (
<figureCitation box="[887,956,1111,1136]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4. 1" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,231,1869]" captionTargetId="figure-74@2.[213,1373,190,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, dorsal habitus without appendages. Scale 0.10 mm. 2. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, antenna, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 3. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.10 mm. 4. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, paramere, lateral view. Scale 0.025 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271484" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271484/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,500,2037]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">
Fore tibia triangular with well developed grasping comb extending beyond apex, black, apex rounded (
<figureCitation box="[1353,1421,1148,1173]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Middle tibia with a pair of long, black setae at posteroventral angle (
<figureCitation box="[939,1009,1183,1208]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Hind trochanter angled upward and bearing a small tubercle projecting beyond posterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[836,905,1220,1245]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,500,2037]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,398,1255,1280]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Apterous female</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[416,525,1255,1280]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Figs. 8–9</figureCitation>
) BL: 2.08; HL: 0.32; HW: 0.60; ANT I–IV: 0.26, 0.22, 0.30, 0.40; INT: 0.36; EYE: 0.12; 
<collectionCode box="[287,324,1292,1315]" country="Czech Republic" name="Západoceské muzeum v Plzni" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" type="Museum">PL</collectionCode>
: 0.30; 
<collectionCode box="[401,446,1292,1315]" country="Thailand" name="Paleontological Collections" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">PW</collectionCode>
: 0.80; FORELEG: FEM: 0.52, TIB: 0.44, TAR I: 0.04, TAR II: 0.20; MIDLEG: FEM: 0.62, TIB: 0.60, TAR I: 0.10, TAR II: 0.24; HINDLEG: FEM: 0.64, TIB: 0.74, TAR I: 0.10, TAR II: 0.24.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,500,2037]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">
Abdomen widened, with tergites I– 
<collectionCode box="[562,582,1364,1387]" country="Canada" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:13946" name="Royal British Columbia Museum - Herbarium" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" type="Museum">V</collectionCode>
concave (
<figureCitation box="[703,774,1364,1389]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) and sternites slightly convex; connexiva slightly turned upward (20º); last abdominal tergite trapezoidal, with posterior margin slightly concave. Genital segment I with divergent lateral margins and posterior margin broadly rounded. Sternite VII bearing two pits on anterolateral margin (
<figureCitation box="[248,318,1471,1496]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Venter of genital segment I with posterior margin broadly rounded (
<figureCitation box="[1127,1198,1471,1496]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Genital segment II smaller and rounded (
<figureCitation box="[397,466,1508,1533]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Grasping comb absent; all tibiae with grooming structures on posteroventral angles; hind trochanter not raised, lacking a tubercle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,500,2037]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,434,1580,1605]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" reason="1">Comparative notes.</emphasis>
Specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="Padilla-Gil &amp; Moreira, 2013" authorityName="Padilla-Gil &amp; Moreira" authorityYear="2013" box="[605,821,1580,1604]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Microvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inguapi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[605,821,1580,1604]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Microvelia inguapi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[831,896,1580,1605]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[831,896,1580,1605]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be diagnosed by the long pronotum which covers the meso- and metanotum; the male with grasping comb extending beyond apex of fore tibia (
<figureCitation box="[1314,1384,1615,1640]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
); all femora without spines; the male hind trochanter raised and bearing a tubercle (
<figureCitation box="[1057,1128,1652,1677]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
); and by the modifications found on the venter of the male and female abdomens (
<figureCitation box="[769,847,1687,1712]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4. 1" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,231,1869]" captionTargetId="figure-74@2.[213,1373,190,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, dorsal habitus without appendages. Scale 0.10 mm. 2. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, antenna, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 3. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.10 mm. 4. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, paramere, lateral view. Scale 0.025 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271484" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271484/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Figs. 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[860,876,1687,1712]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,500,2037]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">
Based on the original description, 
<taxonomicName authority="Padilla-Gil &amp; Moreira, 2013" authorityName="Padilla-Gil &amp; Moreira" authorityYear="2013" box="[596,721,1724,1748]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Microvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inguapi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[596,619,1725,1748]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[636,721,1725,1748]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">inguapi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[731,797,1724,1749]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[731,797,1724,1749]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="J. Polhemus &amp; Hogue, 1972" authorityName="J. Polhemus &amp; Hogue" authorityYear="1972" box="[952,1433,1724,1749]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Microvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inquilina">
<emphasis box="[952,1093,1724,1748]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">M. inquilina</emphasis>
J. Polhemus &amp; Hogue, 1972
</taxonomicName>
. They share similar habitats, and general shape of body, antennae, apical abdominal segments of the male, and the shape of the male paramere are similar. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. Polhemus &amp; Hogue" authorityYear="1972" box="[729,869,1796,1820]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Microvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inquilina">
<emphasis box="[729,869,1796,1820]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">M. inquilina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is smaller (male BL: 1.15; female BL: 1.33); the metanotum is not covered by the pronotum; no modifications are found on the legs; and the grasping comb of the fore tibia is short.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,500,2037]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,1903,1928]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" reason="1">Habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Padilla-Gil &amp; Moreira, 2013" authorityName="Padilla-Gil &amp; Moreira" authorityYear="2013" box="[308,525,1904,1928]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Microvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inguapi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[308,525,1904,1928]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Microvelia inguapi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[536,604,1903,1928]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[536,604,1903,1928]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
has been collected in two estuaries. Chilvi was characterized by an air temperature of 25 ºC, a water temperature of 26.5 ºC, pH 6, dissolved oxygen 65%, conductivity 1 S/m, depth&gt; 
<quantity metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" unit="m" value="1.0">1 m</quantity>
, and substrate with numerous crab holes. Inguapi had an air temperature of 25.5 ºC, a water temperature of 27 ºC, pH 6, dissolved oxygen 108%, conductivity 1 S/m, and depth&gt; 
<specimenCount box="[906,953,2012,2037]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" type="generic">
<quantity box="[906,949,2012,2037]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" unit="m" value="1.0">1 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
</paragraph>
